<Layout title="Research: Cancer Biology">

  <div class="flex items-cejnter gap-4 mb-6">
    <p class="text-justify leading-tight text-sm">
      <b>Gynecological cancers:</b> We apply multiomics integration methods to better understand 
      the tumor biology of gynecological cancers. In collaboration with 
      NCI's Clinical Tumor Analysis Consortyium (CPTAC) we have described the 
      proteogenomic landscape of endometrial cancer (EC)
      (<i><u><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cell.2020.01.026" target="_blank">Dou & Kawaler et al. Cell 2020</a></u></i>,
      <i><u><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ccell.2023.07.007" target="_blank">Dou & Katsnelson et al. Cancer Cell 2023</a></u></i>), and
      Ovarian Cancer (OV)
      (<i><u><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cell.2016.05.069" target="_blank">Zhang et al., Cell 2016</a></u></i>).
      We have integrated proteogenomics with histopathology imaging data using deep learning 
      (<i><u><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.xcrm.2021.100400" target="_blank">Hong et al. Cell Reports Medicine 2021</a></u></i>.
      We have investigated the role of retrotransposons in EC and OV tumor biology and 
      its relationship to p53 mutation, copy number alteration, and S phase checkpoint
      (<i><u><a href="https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.2115999119" target="_blank">McKerrow et al. PNAS 2021</a></u></i>). 
      We are also investigating the relayionship between the tumor microenvironment and 
      the success of immune checkpoint inhibition therapy in endometrial and cervical cancer using 
      mspatial omics approaches.

    </p>
